==== CoQ10 and Acylcarnitine Profile

Coenzyme Q10 (CoQ10) deficiency has been documented in ME/CFS: Maes et al.\ (2009) found that 44.8% of patients had plasma CoQ10 below the lowest control value, with lower CoQ10 correlating with fatigue, autonomic, and neurocognitive symptoms ($n = 58$) @Maes2009CoQ10. CoQ10 has been proposed as both a biomarker of mitochondrial electron transport chain dysfunction and a marker of treatment response. A limitation of total plasma CoQ10 as a biomarker is that it cannot distinguish deficiency driven by oxidative _consumption_ (infection-driven, with inflammation as a downstream amplifier; see Speculation @spec:coq10-infection-consumption) from deficiency driven by impaired _biosynthesis_; the ubiquinol:ubiquinone redox ratio, rather than total CoQ10, has been proposed as a consumption-specific measure (Prediction @pred:coq10-redox-biomarker, Open Question @oq:coq10-consumption-vs-biosynthesis).
Acylcarnitine profiles reflect fatty acid beta-oxidation capacity via the carnitine shuttle. Long-chain acylcarnitines (C18:1, C18:2) are 30–40% lower in ME/CFS patients compared to controls, suggesting reduced carnitine palmitoyltransferase-I (CPT-I) activity and impaired mitochondrial fatty acid import. Reduced free carnitine and total carnitine are also documented, correlating with functional capacity.

